            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born and raised in West Oakland, Marcus Sari\u2019s world was shaped by the hum of his father\u2019s auto shop and the ambition his mother, a school administrator, instilled in him. He was taught the value of working with both his hands and his head. While his friends chased tech start-up dreams in the 90s, Marcus saw a more tangible future in the systems that supported them. He initially followed a hands-on path, working in a shipping warehouse in the Port of Oakland after high school.\n\nA persistent back strain at 25 was the catalyst for change. Realizing that brute force had a shelf life, he enrolled at City College of San Francisco, earning an Associate's degree in Logistics and Supply Chain Management. This credential was his ticket into the unseen skeleton of the tech boom. He transitioned from moving boxes to maintaining the buildings that housed the data inside them. Today, as a Data Center Facilities Technician, he is a guardian of the digital world\u2019s physical body, responsible for the complex power, cooling, and security systems that keep servers online.\n\nHis move across the bay to San Francisco a decade ago followed an amicable divorce. He wanted a fresh start and found a surprising peace in the foggy quiet of the Outer Sunset. His 8.5-mile commute to a data center in South San Francisco is a daily ritual, a time for him to listen to history podcasts that feel a world away from his technical work.\n\nMarcus\u2019s life is one of structured contentment. His social circle is small but loyal\u2014a weekly phone call with his daughter, Imani, who is studying at UC Davis, and weekend get-togethers with a few colleagues to watch games. He finds satisfaction in his meticulously organized garage and the flawless operation of his facility. His ambitions are grounded: he wants to see Imani graduate debt-free and dreams of one day taking a long trip to Egypt to see the ancient engineering marvels he\u2019s only read about. Marcus is a man who understands systems, both electrical and personal, and has built a life of quiet stability in a city defined by chaotic growth."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He was fourteen, watching his father lay out every socket from a sprawling set onto a clean shop rag under the hum of fluorescent lights. \u201cEverything has its place, Marcus,\u201d his dad said, not looking up. \u201cYou take care of the system, the system takes care of the work.\u201d The smell of grease and the neat, metallic rows were calming. It wasn't about the tools; it was a philosophy. That quiet lesson in West Oakland became the blueprint for his own meticulously organized garage and the flawless order he maintains at his facility.\n\n2. He remembers the exact cardboard box\u2014heavy, with \"MACHINE PARTS\" stamped on the side. As he hoisted it in the Port of Oakland warehouse, a searing white-hot pain shot up his spine. In that moment of blinding agony, he didn't just feel the strain on his muscle; he felt the limit of his future. That pain, at age twenty-five, was a command: find a different way. It was the humbling spark that pushed him from brute force to the structured logic of City College, a choice that saved his body.\n\n3. The first night in the Outer Sunset, his boxes were still taped shut. He stood at the window, expecting the city\u2019s noise but hearing only the distant moan of a foghorn. A thick, grey blanket of fog swallowed the streetlights, erasing the world. It wasn't lonely; it was profoundly peaceful. After the shared life across the bay, this quiet solitude felt like a gift. He had chosen this new system for himself, and in the muffled silence following his divorce, he knew it was the right one.\n\n4. The alert screamed from his phone at 3 AM a few years ago: a primary cooling unit had failed. On the data center floor, the air was already thick with heat, a tangible threat to the humming server racks. Amid the rising panic of the on-site junior tech, Marcus felt a surge of engineered calm. He knew the protocols, the overrides, the redundancies. An hour later, with the backup system running perfectly, the crisis was over. In the quiet, he felt deep satisfaction. He was the unseen guardian.\n\n5. During their last weekly call, Imani excitedly detailed a complex agricultural science project. He listened, picturing her in a lab at UC Davis, and felt a surge of profound purpose. Every steady hum from the server racks he maintained, every power system he checked, was a quiet contribution to this moment. His stable, systematic work was the invisible scaffolding supporting her dreams. Ensuring she could graduate debt-free wasn't an abstract goal; it was the most important system he would ever build and maintain."
